Here’s a breakdown of how each component in your setup works, based on your Nginx config and your port assignments:

⸻

✅ 1. Backend API — Port 3001
	•	Runs on: http://localhost:3001
	•	Proxied by Nginx at: https://ai.ecomexperts.io/api
	•	Used for: Handling all dynamic API requests — anything like authentication, data fetch, CRUD operations.
	•	Nginx section:

location /api {
    proxy_pass http://localhost:3001;
    ...
}

⸻

✅ 2. Frontend — Port 443 (via Nginx)
	•	NOT running on a Node.js port like 3000
	•	Built once (e.g., with React/Vue) into static files (HTML, CSS, JS)
	•	Served directly by Nginx from:

/var/www/autominer/frontend/dist
	•	URL: https://ai.ecomexperts.io/

So no Node process is “listening” here — it’s just static file hosting.
⸻

✅ 3. Job Runner — Port 3002
	•	A background service for handling async tasks like:
	•	Queue processing
	•	Email dispatch
	•	Scheduled tasks
	•	Always runs on localhost:3002, not exposed publicly
	•	No Nginx proxy for this by default (unless you add it)
⸻

✅ 4. Analysis Service — Port 3003
	•	A separate microservice for:
	•	Running ML models
	•	Doing heavy data processing
	•	Possibly returning analysis results
	•	Also always runs on localhost:3003
	•	No public exposure via Nginx unless explicitly added
⸻

🧠 How They Interact:

Component	Port	Publicly Exposed?	Nginx Role
Backend API	3001	✅ via /api	Proxied to /api
Frontend	443	✅ main website	Served as static HTML
Job Runner	3002	❌	Internal background processing
Analysis Service	3003	❌	Called internally by backend


⸻

Let me know if you want to set up Nginx to expose job-runner or analysis-runner under specific routes like /jobs or /analysis.